04349nam a22006135i 9780231544351DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016034850  a(OCoLC)984686846  a97802315443517 a10.7312/teeu182762doi  a(DE-B1597)480316  a(OCoLC)979994601  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDS822.2b.B8813 2017 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a952/.0252231 aTeeuwen, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLust, Commerce, and Corruption :bAn Account of What I Have Seen and Heard, by an Edo Samurai /cKate Wildman Nakai, Mark Teeuwen.  aabridged edition 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b15 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTranslations from the Asian Classics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tMeasures -- tCurrencies -- tMaps -- tPart 1. Buyō Inshi and His Times -- tPart 2. Matters of the World: An Account of What I Have Seen and Heard -- tPrologue -- tChapter 1 -- tChapter 2 -- tChapter 3 -- tChapter 4 -- tChapter 5 -- tChapter 6 -- tChapter 7 -- tEditions and References -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy 1816, Japan had recovered from the famines of the 1780s and moved beyond the political reforms of the 1790s. Despite persistent economic and social stresses, the country seemed headed for a new period of growth. The idea that the shogunate would not last forever was far from anyone's mind.Yet, in that year, an anonymous samurai produced a scathing critique of Edo society. Writing as Buyo Inshi, "a retired gentleman of Edo," he expressed in An Account of What I Have Seen and Heard a profound despair with the state of the realm. Seeing decay wherever he turned, Buyo feared the world would soon descend into war.In his anecdotes, Buyo shows a sometimes surprising familiarity with the shadier aspects of Edo life. He speaks of the corruption of samurai officials; the suffering of the poor in villages and cities; the operation of brothels; the dealings of blind moneylenders; the selling and buying of temple abbotships; and the dubious strategies seen in law courts. Perhaps it was the frankness of his account that made him prefer to stay anonymous.A team of Edo specialists undertook the original translation of Buyo's work. This abridged edition streamlines this translation for classroom use, preserving the scope and emphasis of Buyo's argument while eliminating repetitions and diversions. It also retains the introductory essay that situates the work within Edo society and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSocial classeszJapanxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aBreen, John.1 aMiyazaki, Fumiko.1 aNakai, Kate Wildman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWalthall, Anne.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/teeu1827640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231544351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231544351/original  a978-3-11-054330-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  aGBV-deGruyter-alles